data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>()`. It checks the type and returns the cast result, giving you a clear test failure instead of an `InvalidCastException`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

The generic overload (MSTest v3+) returns the typed object so you can continue asserting on it. If you're on an older version, the non-generic form `Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler))` works too, but you'd still need a cast afterward for property access.
